.TH SIMPLECALL 1 "March 2026" "simplecall" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
simplecall \- perform basic syscalls with given arguments
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B simplecall
.I "syscall-id"
.RI [ argument ]...
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B simplecall
decodes each
.I argument
and passes the decoded values to the syscall identified by
.IR syscall-id .

Each argument has the form:
.PP
.RS
\fIspec\fR:\fIdata\fR
.RE
.PP
Supported specifiers are:
.TP
.B i8, i16, i32, i64
Signed integer.
.I data
is parsed as integer text (decimal by default, \fB0o\fR prefix for octal, \fB0x\fR prefix for hexadecimal), converted to the platform's widest integer, truncated to the requested width, then sign-extended to the platform
.B long
used for syscall arguments.
.TP
.B u8, u16, u32, u64
Unsigned integer.
.I data
is parsed as integer text (decimal by default, \fB0o\fR prefix for octal, \fB0x\fR prefix for hexadecimal), converted to the platform's widest integer, truncated to the requested width, then zero-extended to the platform
.B long
used for syscall arguments.
.TP
.B s
String.
.I data
is passed as a pointer to a C-style string buffer.
.TP
.B b
Binary buffer.
.I data
is interpreted as hexadecimal bytes (two hex digits per byte) and passed as a pointer to the allocated buffer.
.TP
.B o
Output buffer.
.I data
is parsed as a size in bytes (decimal, \fB0o\fR, or \fB0x\fR) and a buffer of that size is allocated; the pointer is passed to the syscall.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Syscall succeeded.
.TP
.B 120
Too many syscall arguments.
.TP
.B 121
Bad argument format/specifier, invalid binary length, or allocation failure in output-buffer path.
.TP
.B 122
Allocation failure in binary-buffer path.
.TP
.B 2..255
A propagated
.B errno
value when syscall fails.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B simplecall 93
Invoke syscall 93 with no arguments.
.TP
.B simplecall 1 i8:123 u64:0xdeadbeefcafebabe
Invoke syscall 1 with two arguments: 123 and 0xdeadbeefcafebabe.
.TP
.B simplecall 2 's: Hello World: from simplecall!' u8:1
Invoke syscall 2 with two arguments: pointer to string " Hello World: from simplecall!" and integer 1.
.TP
.B simplecall 3 b:aabbccdd
Invoke syscall 3 with one argument: pointer to 4-byte buffer AA BB CC DD.
.SH NOTES
This program does not impose semantics on the syscall and does not interpret successful syscall return values.
.PP
Current source is only tested for LoongArch64 compatibility.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR syscall (2),
.BR errno (3)
